# Single source of truth

Each piece of data (a list, a set of ids, a config value, a FormID, a default)
must have **exactly one** authoritative definition. Never maintain the same
values in two places — they drift, and duplicates hide bugs.

This burned a sibling project: its position ids lived in BOTH a text file AND a
hard-coded array in the script. Because the two matched, nobody could tell which
was actually in use, and a broken file read was undetectable.

## Rules

- Define data once. Everything else **reads** from that one source.
- If code needs a value that also lives in a file/record, read it from the
  file/record — do not re-declare it in code.
- Constants that mirror external records (FormIDs, EDIDs, ids) must be the ONLY
  copy and should be covered by a contract test that verifies they still match
  the source (see `tools/test_blade_detect_contract.py` for the pattern).
- A default/placeholder is allowed only when it is clearly NOT a duplicate of the
  real data (see `no-hardcoded-fallbacks`).

## Example

```papyrus
; BAD — same ids defined in a data file and again here (two sources of truth)
Lines[0] = "value that is also line 1 of the file"

; GOOD — the file is the ONLY source; code just reads it
String[] raw = GardenOfEden.GetLinesFromFile(FILE, PATH)
```

If you find yourself copy-pasting values that exist elsewhere, stop and read from
the original instead.
